# **1\. Introduction** {#1.-introduction}

## **1.1. Requirement Overview** {#1.1.-requirement-overview}

***What is (CU)2M***  
The primary goal of (CU)2M is to provide assistance to university students in their academic planning. Addressing impediments of navigating convoluted course requirements, and creating effective course schedules.  
***Main features***

- To search course and course details from the course list available.  
- To interact with a canvas grid which has dependency arrows among related courses. Warnings are raised if conflicts happen (e.g. repeated course).   
- To save and edit different course plans.   
- To show the course plan in vertex-edge graph mode.

The application should handle multiple logged in users.   
The application should store an "unlimited" number of plans for each user.

## **1.2. Quality Goals** {#1.2.-quality-goals}

| No. | Quality | Rationale |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 1 | Performance | Response time under 4 seconds with 100 concurrent users |
| 2 | Usability | Intuitive drag-and-drop interface for non-technical users |
| 3 | Maintainability | Strict guidelines to enforce rules such that coding style and naming remain consistent to enhance collaboration, readability, and code quality. |
| 4 | Testability | Comprehensive logging and rigorous testing processes to ensure reliable code |

## **1.3. Stakeholders** {#1.3.-stakeholders}

| Role |  | Interest |
| :---- | ----- | :---- |
| Students |  | Primary users demanding intuitive course planning |

# **2\. Architecture Constraints** {#2.-architecture-constraints}

## **2.1. Technical Constraints** {#2.1.-technical-constraints}

- Language: JavaScript (Frontend), Python/Node.js (Backend)  
  - Frontend Frameworks: Next.js, TailwindCSS  
  - Backend Framework: Flask  
- Database: MongoDB  
- Running environment: Dockerized containers running in Linux

## **2.2. Organizational Constraints** {#2.2.-organizational-constraints}

- IDE independent project setup: Any editor is OK. The software must be runnable using the command line for development.  
- Configuration and version control / management: Private git repository (which is stored on GitHub) with a complete commit history will be adopted. Feature branching will be used for branching in the repository. For feature branches, it should start with “feature/new-feature-name”; for bugs fixes and patches, it should start with “patch/new-patch-name”.  
- Testing: GitHub workflow will be set up to ensure it is runnable (startable) at least. Tests using pytest should be added for each new feature.

## **2.3. Conventions** {#2.3.-conventions}

- Coding conventions and Naming conventions: For Python programs, they must follow conventions set in PEP 8 ([https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/](https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/)). Black ([https://black.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html](https://black.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html)) and Ruff will be used to enforce coding conventions; for Javascript programs, they must adhere to AirBnB's Javascript styling guide ([https://airbnb.io/javascript/](https://airbnb.io/javascript/)). Prettier ([https://prettier.io/](https://prettier.io/)) and related babel presets ([https://www.npmjs.com/package/babel-preset-airbnb](https://www.npmjs.com/package/babel-preset-airbnb)) will be installed to enforce this coding convention.  
- Folder organization conventions: For frontend code, official guidelines ([https://nextjs.org/docs/app/getting-started/project-structure](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/getting-started/project-structure)) is used. For backend code, currently there are no conventions but clarity is the key. The rule of thumb is that functions with drastic purposes should be separated.

# **3\. System Architecture** {#3.-system-architecture}

Fig. 1 in appendix I shows the architectural structure we have chosen for the development. The system follows a client-server architecture with the following components:

1. Frontend (Client):  
   * Built using Next.js for dynamic UI.  
   * Communicates with the backend via RESTful APIs.  
   * Features:   
     1. Login/Signup Page: Allow users to login or create account with license key  
     2. Account Management Page: Enables users to manage their profiles and account settings  
     3. Dashboard: Provides an overview of past plans and allow user to create new plans  
     4. Course Plan Edit Page: A tool for creating or editing course plans including:  
        1. Vertex-edge Viewing Mode: Displays course plans in a structure based on vertices and edges (likely a graph representation).  
        2. Canvas Grid Viewing Mode: Allows users to work with course plans in a grid-like interface.  
        3. Search Box: Allow users to search for courses to be added to the course plan.  
2. Backend (Server):  
   * Flask is used for its simplicity and scalability on RESTful APIs building. It is compatible with MongoDB.  
   * The MVC design pattern is followed due to the following reasons: 1\. its nature of facilitating significant user interaction, and 2\. the separation of layers, which provides modularity, scalability, flexibility, and testability.  
   * Responsible for processing requests, managing data, and providing services to the front-end through RESTful API endpoints  
   * Components:  
     1. User Management: Handles user-related operations like create account with license key, authentication, retrieval, and updates to user profiles  
     2. License Key Management: Manages licensing logic, such as generating or validating license keys. This subsystem also interacts with the email API endpoint to send license-related notifications to users.  
     3. Course Plans Management: Facilitates the creation, modification, and retrieval of course plans. In implementation, it consists of 3 sub components. Namely 1\. Course Plan Management 2\. Semester Plan Management 3\. Course Query Service  
3. Database:  
   * MongoDB for flexible data storing.  
   * The database is the primary storage layer for:  
     1. User data  
     2. Course data (eg. details and dependencies)  
     3. Course plans  
     4. Licensing information  
   * It is accessed by all major back-end components for reading and writing data.  
4. External Services:  
   * Email service for license key distribution and sending account-related activity notifications.

Additionally, by following this architecture and structure, in the future, we can further extend the (CU)2M system into a mobile application since the backend will share the same components in the backend. Integration with the existing CUSIS system would also be convenient.

## **4.2 Data Flow** {#4.2-data-flow}

Fig. 2 in appendix I shows an overview of the data flow in the (CU)2M system.

When logging in, the user sends credentials (i.e. username and password) to the authentication service, which would be verified with the User table. 

When a user is registering for an account, the system sends registration data (e.g. username, password) to the account management system, which would then:

1. verify if the license key is valid by comparing the hashed values;  
2. store the credentials in the User collection if the license key is valid.

After logging in, via the dashboard, the user sends “course plan requests” (create new course plan/edit existing course plan) to the Course Plan Management component, which performs CRUD on the CoursePlan collection. It further passes the course plan’s id to the Semester Plan Management, which would, according to the the value of \`year\` and \`semester\` of the semester plan, render the grid of semester plans. The system reads through the course list of each semester plan, then creates a course block in the semester column and passes the course id to the “Course Query Service” component for details to be displayed in each course block.

Edits of courses in the individual semester plan would be transmitted to Semester Plan Management as semester plan requests, and CRUD operation performed on the Semester Plan table per request.

Users can use a search box to enter their query for finding courses to add. The search request is sent directly to the Course Query Service component, which retrieves the list of courses the user is looking for.

ER diagram is attached (Fig. 3\) in appendix I for more details between entities. 

# **5\. Interface Design** {#5.-interface-design}

## **5.1 Internal Interfaces** {#5.1-internal-interfaces}

Internal interfaces apply the RESTful design due to its wide use, mature community, and high maintainability.

### **5.1.1 User**

| Interfaces | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| POST /api/user/login | Log the user in. |
| POST /api/user/logout | Log the user out. |
| POST /api/user/signup | Register an account with a given license key. |
| POST /api/user/forgot-password | Send an email to the user for password resetting. |
| PUT /api/user/change-password | Change the user’s password. |

### **5.1.2 Course Plan**

| Interfaces | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| GET /api/course-plans | Return all course plans of the user. |
| GET /api/course-plans/{id} | Return the course plan with the specified ID, including all semester plans of the course plan. |
| POST /api/course-plans | Create a new course plan. |
| POST /api/course-plans/{id} | Duplicate the course plan from the specified ID. |
| PUT /api/course-plans/{id} | Update the course plan with the specified ID. |
| DELETE /api/course-plans/{id} | Delete the course plan with the specified ID. |

### **5.1.3 Semester Plan**

| Interfaces | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| GET /api/semester-plans/{id} | Return the semester plan with the specified ID. |
| POST /api/semester-plans/{id} | Create a new semester plan that belongs to a specific course plan ID. |
| PUT /api/semester-plans/{id} | Update the semester plan with the specified ID. |
| DELETE /api/semester-plans/{id} | Delete the semester plan with the specified ID. |

### **5.1.4 Course**

| Interfaces | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| GET /api/courses?code={id} | Return information of multiple courses with the specified course code. Indicate multiple courses through multiple query parameters. E.g.: /api/courses?code=ENGG2020\&code=CSCI3100 |

## **5.2 External Interfaces** {#5.2-external-interfaces}

### **5.2.1 Email Service**

| Interfaces | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| SMTP smtp.gmail.com | Send email to users. |

## **5.3 Exceptions** {#5.3-exceptions}

5.3.1 List of Expected User Exceptions

| Name | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| InvalidCredentials (invalid\_credentials) | The user has entered a wrong credential (i.e. username and/or password). |
| InvalidSession (invalid\_session) | The session of the page is invalid (e.g. the password reset session is expired). |
| InvalidLicense (invalid\_license) | The license key user entered is invalid. |
| UsernameTaken (username\_taken) | The username entered in registration has already been taken by other users. |
| InvalidNames (invalid\_names) | User has entered prohibited symbols in the name field. |

### **5.3.2 Exception Handling**

When the services raise exceptions, user requests are ignored and the system informs the user with a warning banner, specifying what went wrong. See 7.4 for related UI design.

# **6\. Component Design** {#6.-component-design}

As Object Oriented Programming is implemented, refer to Fig. 4 for the class diagram and class definitions of componentes 1, 3-6.

## **6.1 Authentication Service** {#6.1-authentication-service}

### **6.1.1 Responsibilities**

- Manage user authentication

### **6.1.2 I/O Specifications**

- interface AuthenticationInput {

  username: string;		// \[a-zA-Z0-9\_\]{5,20}  
  password: string;		// 12+ chars, mixed case  
}

- interface AuthenticationOutput {

  success: boolean;  
  error?: "invalid\_credentials";  
}

### **6.1.3 Algorithms**

#### *6.1.3.1 Credential validation*

Input: Username and password.  
Step:

1. Find the user with the specified username. If no such user, raise an InvalidCredential exception.  
2. Use bcrypt(12) to hash the input password.  
3. Compare the hash of the input password. If the result matches with the password hash of the user, return a successful response. Otherwise, raise an InvalidCredential exception.

## **6.2 Password Reset Service** {#6.2-password-reset-service}

### **6.2.1 Responsibilities**

- Allow users to reset password if they forget it.  
- Generate a temporary link for password reset.  
- Verify account ownership.

### **6.2.2 I/O Specification**

- interface PasswordResetInput {

  email: string;  
}

- interface PasswordResetOutput {

  success: boolean;  
  error?: "invalid\_session";  
}

### **6.2.3 Algorithm**

#### *6.2.3.1 Account ownership verification*

Input: email.  
Steps:

1. Find an active user with the specified email.  
2. If such a user is found, create a temporary password reset session and send them an email that contains a link to the session with the SMTP interface. Otherwise, do nothing in this step.  
3. Regardless of whether the user is found or not, redirect the user to a page informing them a password reset link has been sent to their email if they have entered the correct email.

#### *6.2.3.2 Password Reset*

Input: password.  
Steps:

1. Check if the password reset session is valid and find its corresponding user. Raise InvalidSession error when the session is invalid.  
2. Create a hash of the new password with bcrypt(12).  
3. Update the password\_hash of the user with this new hash.

## **6.3 Account Management** {#6.3-account-management}

### **6.3.1 Responsibilities**

- Manage user identity  
- Handle two-step registration with email/license validation  
- Handle profile updates and account lifecycle  
- Maintain academic major information

### **6.3.2 I/O Specification**

- interface RegistrationInput {

  email: string;  
  license\_key: string;	// Plaintext key provided to user  
  username: string;		// \[a-zA-Z0-9\_\]{5,20}  
  password: string;		// 12+ chars, mixed case  
  first\_name: string;	// \[a-zA-Z0-9\_\]{5,20}  
  last\_name: string;		// \[a-zA-Z0-9\_\]{5,20}  
}

- interface RegistrationResponse {

  success: boolean;  
  error?: "invalid\_license" | "username\_taken" | "invalid\_names";  
}

### **6.3.3 Algorithm**

#### *6.3.3.1 Pre-Creation Batch Process*

Input: List of emails  
Output: Pre-created inactive user records  
Step:

1. For each (email, key) pair, use bcrypt(12) to generate a hash of license key(license\_hash) and insert the following into users: (\_id=ObjectId, email, license\_hash, activated\_at=0)

#### *6.3.3.2 Registration Validation:*

Input: email, license key, username, password, first name, last name.  
Steps:

1. Find an inactive user with the specified email.  
2. Verify if bcrypt(license\_key) matches with license\_hash.  
3. Check if the username is available.  
4. Validate name formats via regex  
5. If any of the steps above fail, raise an InvalidInput exception.  
6. Hash password with bcrypt(12).  
7. Update record with credentials and activated\_at=now

## **6.4 Course Plan Management** {#6.4-course-plan-management}

### **6.4.1 Responsibilities**

- Coordinate semester plan relationships  
- Manage academic roadmap creation/modification

### **6.4.2 I/O Specification**

- interface CoursePlanCreate {	// \`favourite\` defaulted to be false

  user\_id: string;  
  name: string;  
  years: number;  
  semesters\_per\_year: number;  
} 

- interface CoursePlanEdit {

  course\_plan\_id: string;  
  name: string;			// 3-50 characters  
}

- interface CoursePlanOutput {

  \_id: string;  
  name: string;  
  user\_id: string;  
  semesters: string\[\];		// Array of SemesterPlan IDs  
  updated\_at: string;		// YYYY-MM-DDTHH:mm:ss.sssZ  
}

### **6.4.3 Algorithms**

Create Course Plan:  
Input: user\_id, name, years, semesters\_per\_year  
Steps: 

1. Create Course Plan  
2. For each i from 1 to years, for each j from 1 to semesters\_per\_year, create a SemesterPlan with year set to i, semester set to j and course\_plan\_id set to the id of the new course plan created in step 1\.  
3. Store all semester plan’s id into semesters

## **6.5 Semester Plan Management** {#6.5-semester-plan-management}

### **6.5.1 Responsibilities**

# **7\. UI Design** {#7.-ui-design}

The UI is designed using Figma. See [this figma project](https://www.figma.com/design/OlTYejye2pGbXuYdn5QwR6/EPICU-APPU-3100-UWU) for more details ([https://www.figma.com/design/OlTYejye2pGbXuYdn5QwR6/EPICU-APPU-3100-UWU](https://www.figma.com/design/OlTYejye2pGbXuYdn5QwR6/EPICU-APPU-3100-UWU)). Also see appendix I Fig.5 for a user flow diagram of the system. The following describes the interactions between users and the webpage.

## **7.1 Login/Signup Interface** {#7.1-login/signup-interface}

### **7.1.1 Login**

- When a user requests to log in to the website, it sends a POST request to /api/user/login.  
- If the user forgets the password, they have to first click the “Forget Password” button, in order to send a POST request to /api/user/forgot-password.

### **7.1.2 Signup**

- When a new user wants to register a new account, they need to switch to the signup page using the “Sign up” button, in order to send a POST request to /api/user/signup.

## **7.2 Dashboard Interface** {#7.2-dashboard-interface}

### **7.2.1 User Management**

- By clicking the profile picture in the top-right hand corner, a pop-up will show up. They can click the logout button to send a POST request to /api/user/logout to logout.

### **7.2.2 Course Plan**

#### *7.2.2.1 Main Display*

- The interface loads all the available course plans for the user by sending a GET request to /api/course-plans.  
- The dashboard first shows the most recent edited plans (in a single row), then by the favourite plans (in a single row), then by all course plans.  
- By hovering a specific plan, the description of it will show up. The information is obtained from the initial GET request to /api/course-plans.  
- By left-clicking a specific plan, the interface will be switched to the course plan interface.  
- By right-clicking a specific plan, the options pop-up will be shown.   
- By clicking the “Create new plan” interface, a plan creation pop-up will be shown.   
- By clicking the star on the top right hand corner of a course plan card, they can add / remove that course plan from their favourite list. A PUT request to /api/course-plans/{id} will be sent.

#### *7.2.2.2 Options Pop-up Panel*

- There are three buttons: “Setting edit”, “Duplicate” and “Delete”.  
- “Settings”: a plan edit pop-up will be shown. It then sends a PUT request to /api/course-plans/{id} to edit.  
- “Duplicate”: sends a POST request to /api/course-plans/{id} to duplicate.  
- “Delete”: sends a DELETE request to /api/course-plans/{id} to delete.

#### *7.2.2.3 Plan Creation Pop-up Panel*

- There are 3 fields to edit: “Name”, “No. of sem” (indicating the number of semesters, available only if the user is creating a new plan) and “Description”.  
- It sends a POST request to /api/course-plan upon completion.

## **7.3 Course Plan Interface** {#7.3-course-plan-interface}

### **7.3.1 Grid Mode**

#### *7.3.1.1 Grid Display*

- The years are displayed from left to right.  
- Users can add a new semester by scrolling the screen to the very right. A panel will be shown and select which year and semester (autumn / spring / summer) will be added. A POST request to /api/semester-plans/{id} will be sent.  
- Each grid is similar to an Excel view, i.e: the user can hover the column lines and add a new column (semester). Again, a POST request to /api/semester-plans/{id} will be sent. The client side will prioritize adding Autumn semester first, then Spring semester, and lastly Summer semester.  
- A delete button is available for deleting a specific semester. A DELETE request to /api/semester-plans/{id} will be sent.  
- Users can click a button located on the top-right hand corner to switch to Vertex-edge Mode.

#### *7.3.1.2 Course Search*

- A scrollable course selection panel is located at the bottom, with a search bar searching against the course code or course title.  
- Users can drag the course block to a specific semester. A PUT request to /api/semester-plans/{id} will be sent.

### **7.3.2 Vertex-edge Mode**

#### *7.3.1.1 Graph Display*

- Courses will normally be coloured first by their respective years, and then by semester (same year will have the same color tone).  
- Directed arrows will be used to indicate the dependency between a course. It is drawn from the ancestor (prerequisite course) to its child (required prerequisite course).  
- Users can hover on the course and a pop-up containing the detailed information about the course will appear. Further clicking the “Highlight” button will highlight the dependency tree.  
- Users can click a button located on the top-right hand corner to switch to Grid Mode.

#### *7.3.1.2 Dependencies*

- For courses with missing / conflicting dependencies, it will be highlighted in red and an exclamation mark will appear alerting the user.   
- The dependency calculation will be made using the properly-formatted boolean infix expression given by a GET request of /api/courses?code={id}. The expression will be first converted to postfix expression using the Shunting Yard Algorithm, and then evaluated using a stack.

## **7.4 Exception Banners** {#7.4-exception-banners}

- A banner appears when a user exception occurs. See 5.3.1 for a list of possible user exceptions.  
- The banner is not interactive, and disappears 10 seconds after appearing.

# **8\. Assumptions and Dependencies** {#8.-assumptions-and-dependencies}

1. Courses’ information for each programme are inputted by the department and are stored in the Course.  
2. License key is sent to their CUHK Link email account beforehand.  
3. Docker is used for development to standardize the development environment.  
4. Users are using either Chrome, Firefox or Safari.  
5. English is the only supported language.  
6. The server runs on hardware with quad-core x86\_64 CPU at 2GHz and 8GB of RAM.
